+## 15. Critical Discovery: Shader Cores Not Powered (2025-12-01)
+
+### 15.1 Root Cause Identified
+
+Debug output during job timeout revealed:
+
+```
+GPU: status=0x00000000 fault=0x00000000 shader_ready=0x0 shader_pwractive=0x0
+```
+
+Despite `shader_present=0x550555` (10 shader cores available), **zero cores are powered or active**.
+
+**This is the root cause of job timeout**: Commands are queued, firmware receives them, but there are no powered shader cores to execute them.
+
+### 15.2 Vendor vs Panthor Power Management Architecture
+
+#### Vendor Driver (kbase) - Host-Controlled Power
+
+The vendor driver has two power management modes based on `firmware_hctl_core_pwr` flag:
+
+1. **Firmware-controlled** (`firmware_hctl_core_pwr = false`): Firmware manages shader power
+2. **Host-controlled** (`firmware_hctl_core_pwr = true`): Host driver explicitly powers cores
+
+When host-controlled (which appears to be the case for G720):
+
+```c
+// mali_kbase_pm_driver.c - KBASE_MCU_HCTL_SHADERS_PEND_ON state
+kbase_pm_invoke(kbdev, KBASE_PM_CORE_SHADER, backend->shaders_avail, ACTION_PWRON);
+// This writes to SHADER_PWRON register (0x180)
+```
+
+**Power-on sequence**:
+1. `global_init()` - Set `GLB_ALLOC_EN` mask, ring doorbell
+2. Wait for firmware acknowledgment
+3. Write `SHADER_PWRON` register with desired core mask
+4. Poll `SHADER_READY` register until cores are ready
+5. Notify MCU via `kbase_csf_firmware_update_core_attr()`
+
+#### Panthor Driver - Firmware-Only Power
+
+Panthor assumes firmware controls shader power:
+
+```c
+// panthor_fw.c - panthor_fw_init_global_iface()
+glb_iface->input->core_en_mask = ptdev->gpu_info.shader_present;
+// Sets which cores firmware CAN use, but doesn't power them on
+panthor_fw_toggle_reqs(glb_iface, req, ack, GLB_CFG_ALLOC_EN | ...);
+// Requests firmware to accept core allocation, but firmware doesn't power cores
+```
+
+**Missing in Panthor**:
+- No direct `SHADER_PWRON` register write
+- No `SHADER_READY` polling
+- No MCU core notification after power-on
+
+### 15.3 Register Analysis
+
+| Register | Offset | Purpose | Vendor Uses | Panthor Uses |
+|----------|--------|---------|-------------|--------------|
+| `SHADER_PRESENT` | 0x100 | Available shader cores | ✅ Read | ✅ Read |
+| `SHADER_READY` | 0x140 | Powered & ready cores | ✅ Poll | ❌ Never read |
+| `SHADER_PWRON` | 0x180 | Power on cores | ✅ Write | ❌ Never write |
+| `SHADER_PWROFF` | 0x1C0 | Power off cores | ✅ Write | ❌ Never write |
+| `SHADER_PWRTRANS` | 0x200 | Cores in transition | ✅ Poll | ❌ Never read |
+| `SHADER_PWRACTIVE` | 0x240 | Currently active cores | ✅ Check | ✅ Debug only |
+| `SHADER_PWRFEATURES` | 0x188 | RTU enable | ✅ Write | ✅ Added |
+
+### 15.4 Proposed Fix
+
+Implement host-controlled shader power for G720 in Panthor:
+
+**Phase 1: Power-on during firmware init**
+
+```c
+// In panthor_fw_init_global_iface() after setting core_en_mask:
+
+/* G720: Power on shader cores before CSG operations */
+if (GPU_ARCH_MAJOR(ptdev->gpu_info.gpu_id) >= 12) {
+    u64 shader_mask = ptdev->gpu_info.shader_present;
+
+    /* Write power-on request */
+    gpu_write64(ptdev, SHADER_PWRON, shader_mask);
+
+    /* Wait for cores to be ready */
+    ret = gpu_read64_poll_timeout(ptdev, SHADER_READY,
+                                   val, (val & shader_mask) == shader_mask,
+                                   100, 2000000);
+    if (ret)
+        drm_warn(&ptdev->base, "Shader power-on timeout: ready=0x%llx, wanted=0x%llx",
+                 val, shader_mask);
+}
+```
+
+**Phase 2: Dynamic power management** (TODO)
+
+After Phase 1 works, implement proper power management:
+- Power down idle cores for power savings
+- Power up cores on demand
+- Handle power state transitions properly
+- Notify MCU when core power state changes
+- Implement `firmware_hctl_core_pwr` equivalent flag for conditional behavior
+
