+# Sky1 G720 GPU Power State Model
+
+## Overview
+
+This document details the CIX Sky1 Immortalis G720 GPU power control architecture, focusing on the HOST_POWER interface and the critical role of reset controller configuration.
+
+## Register Blocks
+
+The G720 has two power control interfaces:
+
+### Legacy GPU_CONTROL Registers (0x100-0x1FF)
+Traditional Mali power registers, works on all architectures:
+- `SHADER_PRESENT` (0x100) - Bitmap of available shader cores
+- `SHADER_READY` (0x140) - Bitmap of powered-on shader cores
+- `SHADER_PWRON` (0x180) - Write to power on shader cores
+- `SHADER_PWROFF` (0x1C0) - Write to power off shader cores
+- `SHADER_PWRTRANS` (0x200) - Power transition in progress
+
+### HOST_POWER Registers (0x800-0xBFF) - G720 Only
+New power control interface for arch >= 12 (G720/Immortalis):
+- `PWR_IRQ_RAWSTAT` (0x800) - Power interrupt raw status
+- `PWR_IRQ_CLEAR` (0x804) - Clear power interrupts
+- `PWR_IRQ_MASK` (0x808) - Power interrupt mask
+- `PWR_STATUS` (0x820) - Power delegation status (64-bit)
+- `PWR_COMMAND` (0x828) - Power command register
+- `PWR_CMDARG` (0x830) - Command argument (core mask, 64-bit)
+- `HOST_POWER_SHADER_PRESENT` (0xA00) - Shader present via HOST_POWER
+- `HOST_POWER_SHADER_READY` (0xA08) - Shader ready via HOST_POWER
+- `HOST_POWER_SHADER_PWRTRANS` (0xA10) - Shader power transition
+- `HOST_POWER_SHADER_PWRACTIVE` (0xA18) - Shader power active
+
+## PWR_STATUS Register Layout
+
+```
+Bit 0:  ALLOW_L2       - Host allowed to control L2 power
+Bit 1:  ALLOW_TILER    - Host allowed to control tiler power
+Bit 8:  ALLOW_SHADER   - Host allowed to control shader power
+Bit 16: DELEGATED_L2   - L2 power delegated to firmware
+Bit 17: DELEGATED_TILER - Tiler power delegated to firmware
+Bit 24: DELEGATED_SHADER - Shader power delegated to firmware
+```
+
+When `ALLOW_*` is set and `DELEGATED_*` is clear, host can control that power domain.
+
+## PWR_COMMAND Values
+
+```c
+PWR_COMMAND_POWER_UP    = 0x10  // Power up domain
+PWR_COMMAND_POWER_DOWN  = 0x11  // Power down domain
+PWR_COMMAND_RESET_HARD  = 0x30  // Hard reset
+PWR_COMMAND_RESET_SOFT  = 0x31  // Soft reset
+
+// Domain selection (bits 8-15)
+PWR_COMMAND_DOMAIN_L2     = 0x000
+PWR_COMMAND_DOMAIN_TILER  = 0x100
+PWR_COMMAND_DOMAIN_SHADER = 0x800
+```
+
+## Sky1 Reset Controllers
+
+The Sky1 GPU device tree defines TWO reset controllers:
+
+```dts
+resets = <&reset_ctrl 0x77>, <&reset_ctrl 0x09>;
+reset-names = "gpu_rcsu_reset", "gpu_reset";
+```
+
+### gpu_rcsu_reset (index 0x77)
+Resets the RCSU (Reset Control Status Unit) at 0x15000000.
+**DO NOT ASSERT THIS AT RUNTIME** - it appears to disable the HOST_POWER interface.
+
+### gpu_reset (index 0x09)
+Resets the GPU IP block at 0x15010000.
+This is the only reset that should be used during normal operation.
+
+## Critical Discovery: Reset Controller Bug
+
+**Root Cause of HOST_POWER returning 0x0:**
+
+Panthor was using `devm_reset_control_array_get_optional_exclusive()` which asserts/deasserts ALL resets (both `gpu_rcsu_reset` and `gpu_reset`).
+
+The vendor driver uses only `gpu_reset`:
+```c
+kbdev->gpu_reset = devm_reset_control_get(kbdev->dev, "gpu_reset");
+```
+
+Asserting `gpu_rcsu_reset` appears to wipe out power management configuration, causing:
+- `PWR_STATUS` to read as 0x0
+- `HOST_POWER_SHADER_PRESENT` to read as 0x0
+- All HOST_POWER registers to be non-functional
+
+**Fix:** Use `devm_reset_control_get_optional_exclusive(dev, "gpu_reset")` to get only the GPU IP reset.
+
+## Power-On Sequence
+
+### Vendor Driver (kbase) Sequence
+1. Power domain on (via generic PM domain)
+2. Enable clocks (core, stacks)
+3. Assert `gpu_reset` via reset_control
+4. Wait 10-20 usec
+5. Deassert `gpu_reset`
+6. Enable Q-channel clock gating (RCSU PGCTRL register)
+7. Read `PWR_STATUS` to verify HOST_POWER is available
+8. If `has_host_pwr_iface`: use HOST_POWER for all power control
+9. Otherwise: fall back to legacy SHADER_PWRON etc.
+
+### Panthor Sequence (after fix)
+1. `panthor_device_init()`: Set initial state to SUSPENDED
+2. `panthor_reset_init()`: Get only `gpu_reset` by name
+3. `pm_runtime_resume_and_get()` triggers `panthor_device_resume()`
+4. `panthor_device_resume()`:
+   - Enable clocks
+   - Call `panthor_platform_reset()`:
+     - Assert/deassert `gpu_reset`
+     - Enable Q-channel clock gating
+5. `panthor_gpu_init()`: Optional soft reset
+6. `panthor_fw_init()`: Load firmware, initialize CSF interface
+7. `panthor_gpu_g720_shader_power_on()`: Power on shaders via HOST_POWER
+
+## Shader Power Control
+
+### Using HOST_POWER (preferred for G720)
+```c
+// Check PWR_STATUS first
+pwr_status = gpu_read64(ptdev, PWR_STATUS);
+if (!(pwr_status & PWR_STATUS_ALLOW_SHADER))
+    return;  // Firmware controls shaders
+
+// Write core mask
+gpu_write64(ptdev, PWR_CMDARG, shader_mask);
+
+// Issue power-up command
+gpu_write(ptdev, PWR_COMMAND,
+          PWR_COMMAND_DOMAIN_SHADER | PWR_COMMAND_POWER_UP);
+
+// Wait for ready
+poll(HOST_POWER_SHADER_READY == shader_mask);
+```
+
+### Using Legacy Registers (fallback)
+```c
+// Write directly to SHADER_PWRON
+gpu_write64(ptdev, SHADER_PWRON, shader_mask);
+
+// Wait for SHADER_READY
+poll(SHADER_READY == shader_mask);
+```
+
+## Vendor Driver Feature Detection
+
+The vendor driver determines HOST_POWER availability via hardware feature flags:
+
+```c
+// In kbase_pm_backend_init()
+kbdev->pm.backend.has_host_pwr_iface =
+    kbase_hw_has_feature(kbdev, KBASE_HW_FEATURE_POWER_CONTROL);
+```
+
+`KBASE_HW_FEATURE_POWER_CONTROL` is set for G720 (tDRx) in `base_hw_features_tDRx_r0p0[]`.
+
+## RCSU (Reset Control Status Unit)
+
+Located at 0x15000000 (separate from GPU at 0x15010000).
+
+Key registers:
+- `PGCTRL` (0x218) - Power gating control
+  - Bit 0: Q-channel clock gating enable
+- `STRAP_PIN1` (0x08) - Core harvesting info
+  - Bits 4-27: Disabled shader core mask
+
+The RCSU manages:
+- Q-channel interface for clock gating requests
+- Core harvesting (disabled cores)
+- Power gating control
+
+## Files Reference
+
+- Panthor reset init: `drivers/gpu/drm/panthor/panthor_device.c:panthor_reset_init()`
+- Panthor platform reset: `drivers/gpu/drm/panthor/panthor_device.c:panthor_platform_reset()`
+- G720 shader power: `drivers/gpu/drm/panthor/panthor_gpu.c:panthor_gpu_g720_shader_power_on()`
+- HOST_POWER regs: `drivers/gpu/drm/panthor/panthor_regs.h`
+
+Vendor references:
+- Reset handling: `cix-drivers-dkms/src/gpu/.../platform/sky1/mali_kbase_runtime_pm.c`
+- Feature detection: `cix-drivers-dkms/src/gpu/.../mali_kbase_hwconfig_features.h`
+- Power driver: `cix-drivers-dkms/src/gpu/.../backend/gpu/mali_kbase_pm_driver.c`
+
+---
+
+## Current Status (2025-12-01)
+
+### HOST_POWER Interface - Non-Functional
+
+Despite applying the reset controller fix, HOST_POWER registers still return 0x0:
+
+```
+Before shader power: MCU_STATUS=0x00000001 PWR_STATUS=0x0000000000000000
+G720: PWR_STATUS=0x0000000000000000 HP_SHADER_PRESENT=0x0
+G720: RETRACT failed, PWR_STATUS still 0x0
+```
+
+Attempted fixes that did NOT resolve HOST_POWER:
+- ✅ Reset controller fix (use only `gpu_reset`)
+- ✅ RCSU mapping and Q-channel clock gating
+- ✅ PWR_COMMAND RETRACT sequence
+
+### Legacy Fallback - Working
+
+Legacy `SHADER_PWRON` register at 0x180 successfully powers shaders:
+
+```
+G720: HOST_POWER unavailable, trying legacy SHADER_PWRON
+G720: legacy shader power-on succeeded (ready=0x550555)
+```
+
+### Current Implementation
+
+`panthor_gpu_g720_shader_power_on()` now implements:
+
+1. Check `PWR_STATUS` for HOST_POWER availability
+2. If `PWR_STATUS == 0`, try RETRACT command (times out)
+3. If `ALLOW_SHADER` not set, fall back to legacy:
+   - Write `shader_mask` to `SHADER_PWRON` (0x180)
+   - Poll `SHADER_READY` (0x140) for completion
+4. Legacy path succeeds: `shader_ready=0x550555`
+
+### Remaining Issue: Shaders Ready but Not Executing
+
+Shaders are powered but not executing jobs:
+- `shader_ready=0x550555` ✅ (powered via legacy)
+- `shader_pwractive=0x0` ❌ (not executing)
+
+## Root Cause Analysis (2025-12-01)
+
+### MCU Shader Power Control Architecture
+
+The vendor driver has a key flag: `firmware_hctl_core_pwr` (firmware host control core power):
+
+- **When `firmware_hctl_core_pwr = false` (default)**:
+  - MCU controls shader core power transitions
+  - Uses `GLB_PWROFF_TIMER` to auto-power-off idle cores
+  - Uses HOST_POWER interface to power on cores when jobs arrive
+  - **This is where Sky1 fails** - HOST_POWER doesn't work
+
+- **When `firmware_hctl_core_pwr = true`**:
+  - Host driver controls shader core power
+  - `GLB_PWROFF_TIMER` is set to 0 (disabled)
+  - MCU just dispatches jobs to already-powered cores
+  - Host uses legacy `SHADER_PWRON` etc. directly
+
+### The Problem on Sky1
+
+1. Panthor sets `poweroff_timer` to a non-zero value (10000 µs)
+2. This tells MCU to manage shader power automatically
+3. MCU tries to power on shader cores via HOST_POWER when jobs arrive
+4. HOST_POWER doesn't respond (PWR_STATUS=0x0)
+5. MCU can't activate cores for jobs
+6. Jobs timeout with `shader_pwractive=0x0`
+
+Our legacy `SHADER_PWRON` write at boot powers cores to READY state, but MCU doesn't know about this and still tries to use HOST_POWER.
+
+### Proposed Fix
+
+Set `poweroff_timer = 0` for Sky1 to disable MCU's shader power management:
+
+```c
+// In panthor_fw.c:panthor_fw_init_global_iface()
+if (of_device_is_compatible(ptdev->base.dev->of_node, "cix,sky1-mali")) {
+    /* Sky1: HOST_POWER is non-functional. Disable MCU power management
+     * so it just dispatches to already-powered cores.
+     */
+    glb_iface->input->poweroff_timer = 0;
+} else {
+    glb_iface->input->poweroff_timer = panthor_fw_conv_timeout(ptdev, PWROFF_HYSTERESIS_US);
+}
+```
+
+With `poweroff_timer = 0`:
+1. MCU won't auto-power-off shader cores
+2. MCU won't try to power on cores (assumes already powered)
+3. MCU just dispatches jobs to cores specified in `core_en_mask`
+4. We power on all cores via legacy path at boot
+5. Jobs should execute successfully
+
+### Vendor Driver Reference
+
+Key files in vendor mali_kbase:
+- `csf/mali_kbase_csf_firmware.c:1619` - Sets `GLB_PWROFF_TIMER` based on `firmware_hctl_core_pwr`
+- `csf/mali_kbase_csf_defs.h:1749` - `firmware_hctl_core_pwr` definition
+- `backend/gpu/mali_kbase_pm_internal.h:872` - `kbase_pm_no_mcu_core_pwroff()`
+
+When `firmware_hctl_core_pwr = true`:
+```c
+pwroff_reg = GLB_PWROFF_TIMER_TIMER_SOURCE_SET(
+    DISABLE_GLB_PWROFF_TIMER, GLB_PWROFF_TIMER_TIMER_SOURCE_SYSTEM_TIMESTAMP);
+// DISABLE_GLB_PWROFF_TIMER = 0
+```
+
+See `docs/csf-interface-comparison.md` Section 16 for detailed analysis.
