+# Vendor Mali DKMS Power Management System - Comprehensive Analysis
+
+## 1. Overview
+
+The vendor Mali driver has a sophisticated power management system designed for Gen12 (G720) GPUs. It supports two distinct power control modes:
+
+1. **Firmware-Controlled Power (MCU controls shader power)**
+2. **Host-Controlled Power (`firmware_hctl_core_pwr = true`)**
+
+The mode selection determines who manages shader core power-on/off during job execution.
+
+---
+
+## 2. HOST_POWER Interface (G720 Arch >= 12)
+
+### 2.1 Register Map (0x800+ region)
+
+| Register | Offset | Description |
+|----------|--------|-------------|
+| `PWR_IRQ_RAWSTAT` | 0x800 | Power IRQ raw status |
+| `PWR_IRQ_CLEAR` | 0x804 | Power IRQ clear |
+| `PWR_IRQ_MASK` | 0x808 | Power IRQ mask |
+| `PWR_IRQ_STAT` | 0x80C | Power IRQ status |
+| `PWR_STATUS` | 0x820 | Power domain status (64-bit) |
+| `PWR_COMMAND` | 0x828 | Power domain command |
+| `PWR_CMDARG` | 0x830 | Power command argument |
+
+### 2.2 HOST_POWER Core Presence/Ready Registers
+
+| Register | Offset | Description |
+|----------|--------|-------------|
+| `HOST_POWER_SHADER_PRESENT` | 0xA00 | Shader cores present |
+| `HOST_POWER_SHADER_READY` | 0xA08 | Shader cores ready |
+| `HOST_POWER_SHADER_PWRTRANS` | 0xA10 | Shader power transitioning |
+| `HOST_POWER_SHADER_PWRACTIVE` | 0xA18 | **Shader cores actively executing** |
+
+### 2.3 PWR_STATUS Register Bits (64-bit)
+
+```c
+// ALLOW bits (indicate domain is allowed to be powered)
+PWR_STATUS_ALLOW_L2_SHIFT      = 0    // L2 allowed
+PWR_STATUS_ALLOW_TILER_SHIFT   = 1    // Tiler allowed
+PWR_STATUS_ALLOW_SHADER_SHIFT  = 8    // Shader allowed
+
+// DELEGATED bits (indicate domain control given to MCU)
+PWR_STATUS_DELEGATED_L2_SHIFT      = 16  // L2 delegated to MCU
+PWR_STATUS_DELEGATED_TILER_SHIFT   = 17  // Tiler delegated to MCU
+PWR_STATUS_DELEGATED_SHADER_SHIFT  = 24  // Shader delegated to MCU
+PWR_STATUS_DELEGATED_NEURAL_SHIFT  = 25  // Neural delegated to MCU
+
+// Other status bits
+PWR_STATUS_RETRACT_PENDING_SHIFT   = 43  // Retract operation pending
+```
+
+### 2.4 PWR_COMMAND Values
+
+| Command | Value | Description |
+|---------|-------|-------------|
+| `PWR_COMMAND_NOP` | 0x00 | No operation |
+| `PWR_COMMAND_POWER_UP` | 0x10 | Power up domain |
+| `PWR_COMMAND_POWER_DOWN` | 0x11 | Power down domain |
+| `PWR_COMMAND_DELEGATE` | 0x20 | **Give control to MCU firmware** |
+| `PWR_COMMAND_RETRACT` | 0x21 | **Take control back from MCU** |
+| `PWR_COMMAND_RESET_HARD` | 0x30 | Hard reset |
+| `PWR_COMMAND_RESET_SOFT` | 0x31 | Soft reset |
+| `PWR_COMMAND_INSPECT` | 0xF0 | Inspect domain status |
+
+### 2.5 Power Domain IDs
+
+```c
+PWR_COMMAND_DOMAIN_L2      = 0x0   // L2 cache
+PWR_COMMAND_DOMAIN_TILER   = 0x1   // Tiler
+PWR_COMMAND_DOMAIN_SHADER  = 0x8   // Shader cores
+PWR_COMMAND_DOMAIN_NEURAL  = 0x9   // Neural engine
+PWR_COMMAND_DOMAIN_BASE    = 0xE   // Base
+PWR_COMMAND_DOMAIN_STACK   = 0xF   // Core stack
+```
+
+---
+
+## 3. Power Control Mode Selection
+
+### 3.1 `has_host_pwr_iface` Flag
+
+Set during PM backend init based on hardware feature:
+
+```c
+// mali_kbase_pm_backend.c:167
+kbdev->pm.backend.has_host_pwr_iface =
+    kbase_hw_has_feature(kbdev, KBASE_HW_FEATURE_POWER_CONTROL);
+```
+
+This indicates whether the GPU supports the HOST_POWER interface (arch >= 12).
+
+### 3.2 `firmware_hctl_core_pwr` Flag
+
+**Critical flag determining who controls shader power:**
+
+```c
+// Set during firmware initialization
+kbdev->csf.firmware_hctl_core_pwr = kbase_pm_no_mcu_core_pwroff(kbdev);
+
+// kbase_pm_no_mcu_core_pwroff() definition:
+static inline bool kbase_pm_no_mcu_core_pwroff(struct kbase_device *kbdev) {
+    return kbdev->pm.backend.csf_pm_sched_flags & CSF_DYNAMIC_PM_CORE_KEEP_ON;
+}
+```
+
+**When `firmware_hctl_core_pwr = true`:**
+- Host driver directly controls shader power via registers
+- MCU firmware does NOT manage shader power
+- `GLB_PWROFF_TIMER` set to 0 (disabled)
+- Host must notify MCU of core changes via `kbase_csf_firmware_update_core_attr()`
+
+**When `firmware_hctl_core_pwr = false`:**
+- MCU firmware manages shader power automatically
+- MCU uses `GLB_PWROFF_TIMER` to power off idle shaders
+- Power control DELEGATED to MCU
+
+### 3.3 Power Policy and `CSF_DYNAMIC_PM_CORE_KEEP_ON`
+
+The `always_on` power policy sets this flag:
+
+```c
+// mali_kbase_pm_defs.h:588
+#define ALWAYS_ON_PM_SCHED_FLAGS                                          \
+    (CSF_DYNAMIC_PM_CORE_KEEP_ON | CSF_DYNAMIC_PM_SCHED_IGNORE_IDLE | \
+     CSF_DYNAMIC_PM_SCHED_NO_TICK)
+```
+
+When the `always_on` policy is active -> `firmware_hctl_core_pwr = true` -> host controls shader power.
+
+---
+
+## 4. DELEGATE/RETRACT Mechanism
+
+### 4.1 Delegation to MCU Firmware
+
+```c
+static int delegate_pm_domain_control_to_fw(struct kbase_device *kbdev, u32 pm_domain) {
+    u64 pwr_cmd = PWR_COMMAND_COMMAND_SET(0, PWR_COMMAND_COMMAND_DELEGATE);
+    pwr_cmd = PWR_COMMAND_DOMAIN_SET(pwr_cmd, pm_domain);
+
+    // Send DELEGATE command
+    kbase_reg_write32(kbdev, HOST_POWER_ENUM(PWR_COMMAND), pwr_cmd);
+
+    // Wait for ALLOW bit cleared and DELEGATED bit set
+    kbase_reg_poll64_timeout(kbdev, HOST_POWER_ENUM(PWR_STATUS), val,
+                             !(val & allow_mask) && (val & delegate_mask), ...);
+}
+
+// Delegate all domains (Tiler, Shader, Neural) at once
+static void delegate_pm_domains_control_to_fw(struct kbase_device *kbdev) {
+    delegate_pm_domain_control_to_fw(kbdev, PWR_COMMAND_DOMAIN_TILER);
+    delegate_pm_domain_control_to_fw(kbdev, PWR_COMMAND_DOMAIN_SHADER);
+    if (has_neural_engine)
+        delegate_pm_domain_control_to_fw(kbdev, PWR_COMMAND_DOMAIN_NEURAL);
+}
+```
+
+### 4.2 Retraction from MCU Firmware
+
+```c
+static int retract_pm_domain_control_from_fw(struct kbase_device *kbdev, u32 pm_domain) {
+    u64 pwr_cmd = PWR_COMMAND_COMMAND_SET(0, PWR_COMMAND_COMMAND_RETRACT);
+    pwr_cmd = PWR_COMMAND_DOMAIN_SET(pwr_cmd, pm_domain);
+
+    // Send RETRACT command
+    kbase_reg_write32(kbdev, HOST_POWER_ENUM(PWR_COMMAND), pwr_cmd);
+
+    // Wait for RETRACT_PENDING to clear
+    kbase_reg_poll64_timeout(kbdev, HOST_POWER_ENUM(PWR_STATUS), val,
+                             !PWR_STATUS_RETRACT_PENDING_GET(val), ...);
+}
+```
+
+### 4.3 When Delegation/Retraction Occurs
+
+In `kbase_pm_l2_update_state()`:
+
+```c
+case KBASE_L2_OFF:
+    if (need_tiler_control(kbdev)) {
+        // Host controls power -> RETRACT from MCU
+        if (backend->pwr_cntl_delegated) {
+            retract_pm_domains_control_from_fw(kbdev);
+            backend->pwr_cntl_delegated = false;
+        }
+    } else {
+        // MCU controls power -> DELEGATE to MCU
+        if (has_host_pwr_iface && !backend->pwr_cntl_delegated) {
+            delegate_pm_domains_control_to_fw(kbdev);
+            backend->pwr_cntl_delegated = true;
+        }
+    }
+```
+
+`need_tiler_control()` returns `true` when `kbase_pm_no_mcu_core_pwroff()` is true (host-controlled mode).
+
+---
+
+## 5. MCU State Machine (Host-Controlled Mode)
+
+When `firmware_hctl_core_pwr = true`, the MCU state machine follows this sequence:
+
+```
+KBASE_MCU_OFF
+    |
+KBASE_MCU_PEND_ON_RELOAD
+    |
+KBASE_MCU_ON_GLB_REINIT_PEND
+    | (firmware_hctl_core_pwr = true)
+KBASE_MCU_HCTL_STACK_PEND_ON     <- Host powers on core stacks
+    |
+KBASE_MCU_HCTL_BASE_PEND_ON      <- Host powers on base domains
+    |
+KBASE_MCU_HCTL_SHADERS_PEND_ON   <- Host powers on shader cores
+    |
+KBASE_MCU_HCTL_CORES_NOTIFY_PEND <- Host notifies MCU via update_core_attr()
+    |
+KBASE_MCU_ON_HWCNT_ENABLE
+    |
+KBASE_MCU_ON
+```
+
+**Key Code:**
+
+```c
+case KBASE_MCU_ON_GLB_REINIT_PEND:
+    if (kbase_csf_firmware_global_reinit_complete(kbdev)) {
+        if (kbdev->csf.firmware_hctl_core_pwr) {
+            // Host powers cores directly
+            kbase_pm_invoke(kbdev, KBASE_PM_CORE_SHADER,
+                            backend->shaders_avail, ACTION_PWRON);
+            backend->mcu_state = KBASE_MCU_HCTL_SHADERS_PEND_ON;
+        } else {
+            // MCU handles power automatically
+            backend->mcu_state = KBASE_MCU_ON_HWCNT_ENABLE;
+        }
+    }
+
+case KBASE_MCU_HCTL_SHADERS_PEND_ON:
+    if (hctl_shader_cores_power_up_done(kbdev, shaders_ready, ...)) {
+        // Notify MCU which cores are powered
+        kbase_csf_firmware_update_core_attr(kbdev, false, true, shaders_ready);
+        backend->mcu_state = KBASE_MCU_HCTL_CORES_NOTIFY_PEND;
+    }
+```
+
+---
+
+## 6. CSF Firmware Interface
+
+### 6.1 Global Interface Registers
+
+| Register | Offset | Description |
+|----------|--------|-------------|
+| `GLB_PWROFF_TIMER` | 0x14 | Shader power-off timer |
+| `GLB_ALLOC_EN_LO` | 0x18 | Shader core allocation mask (low 32 bits) |
+| `GLB_ALLOC_EN_HI` | 0x1C | Shader core allocation mask (high 32 bits) |
+| `GLB_PWROFF_TIMER_CONFIG` | 0x88 | Power-off timer configuration |
+
+### 6.2 `GLB_PWROFF_TIMER` Settings
+
+```c
+static void set_shader_poweroff_timer(struct kbase_csf_fw_io *fw_io) {
+    if (kbdev->csf.firmware_hctl_core_pwr) {
+        // Host controls power -> DISABLE timer
+        pwroff_reg = GLB_PWROFF_TIMER_TIMER_SOURCE_SET(
+            DISABLE_GLB_PWROFF_TIMER,  // 0
+            GLB_PWROFF_TIMER_TIMER_SOURCE_SYSTEM_TIMESTAMP);
+    } else {
+        // MCU controls power -> use configured timeout
+        pwroff_reg = kbdev->csf.mcu_core_pwroff_dur_count;
+    }
+
+    kbase_csf_fw_io_global_write(fw_io, GLB_PWROFF_TIMER, pwroff_reg);
+}
+```
+
+**When `GLB_PWROFF_TIMER = 0`:**
+- MCU does NOT automatically power off idle shaders
+- MCU expects host to manage shader power
+
+### 6.3 `enable_endpoints_global()` - Setting Core Allocation Mask
+
+```c
+static void enable_endpoints_global(struct kbase_csf_fw_io *fw_io, u64 shader_core_mask) {
+    // Write the mask of available shader cores to MCU
+    kbase_csf_fw_io_global_write(fw_io, GLB_ALLOC_EN_LO, shader_core_mask & U32_MAX);
+    kbase_csf_fw_io_global_write(fw_io, GLB_ALLOC_EN_HI, shader_core_mask >> 32);
+
+    // Request MCU acknowledge the configuration
+    set_global_request(fw_io, GLB_REQ_CFG_ALLOC_EN_MASK);
+}
+```
+
+This tells MCU which cores are available for job allocation.
+
+### 6.4 `kbase_csf_firmware_update_core_attr()` - Notifying MCU
+
+```c
+void kbase_csf_firmware_update_core_attr(struct kbase_device *kbdev,
+                                         bool update_core_pwroff_timer,
+                                         bool update_core_mask,
+                                         u64 core_mask) {
+    if (update_core_mask)
+        enable_endpoints_global(fw_io, core_mask);
+    if (update_core_pwroff_timer)
+        set_shader_poweroff_timer(fw_io);
+
+    // Ring doorbell to notify MCU
+    kbase_csf_ring_doorbell(kbdev, CSF_KERNEL_DOORBELL_NR);
+}
+```
+
+---
+
+## 7. `hctl_*` Functions (Host Control Helpers)
+
+These functions check power state transitions when host controls power:
+
+| Function | Purpose |
+|----------|---------|
+| `hctl_shader_cores_active()` | Check if shaders are actively executing |
+| `hctl_shader_cores_power_up_done()` | Check shader power-up complete |
+| `hctl_shader_cores_power_down_done()` | Check shader power-down complete |
+| `hctl_cores_power_up_done()` | Generic core power-up check |
+| `hctl_cores_power_down_done()` | Generic core power-down check |
+| `hctl_tiler_power_up_done()` | Check/initiate tiler power-up |
+| `hctl_l2_power_down()` | Initiate L2 power-down |
+| `hctl_neural_engines_active()` | Check neural engine activity |
+
+**Example - `hctl_shader_cores_active()`:**
+
+```c
+static bool hctl_shader_cores_active(struct kbase_device *kbdev, u64 shaders_ready) {
+    u64 shaders_active = kbase_pm_get_active_cores(kbdev, KBASE_PM_CORE_SHADER);
+    bool cores_are_active = (shaders_active != 0);
+
+    // Also check neural engine activity
+    cores_are_active = cores_are_active || hctl_neural_engines_active(kbdev);
+    return cores_are_active;
+}
+```
+
+---
+
+## 8. Sky1-Specific Power Code
+
+### 8.1 Platform Init Sequence
+
+```c
+// mali_kbase_config_sky1.c
+static int kbase_platform_sky1_init(struct kbase_device *kbdev) {
+    err = sky1_gpu_attach_pd(kbdev);  // Attach power domains
+
+    // Read harvesting info from RCSU
+    harvesting_reg_val = sky1_rcsu_reg_read32(kbdev, GPU_RCSU_HWREG_STRAP_PIN1);
+    // ... configure based on harvesting
+}
+```
+
+### 8.2 Power-On Sequence
+
+```c
+// mali_kbase_runtime_pm.c
+/*
+ * sky1 GPU power probe sequence:
+ * Power domain on->clock enable->IP Reset assert->IP Reset de-assert
+ */
+static int pm_callback_power_on(struct kbase_device *kbdev) {
+    enable_gpu_power_control(kbdev);
+
+    if (need_reset_flag) {
+        execute_gpu_reset(kbdev);                    // Assert/deassert reset
+        gpu_qchannel_clock_gating_switch(kbdev, true); // Enable Q-channel
+        need_reset_flag = false;
+    }
+}
+
+static void execute_gpu_reset(struct kbase_device *kbdev) {
+    reset_control_assert(kbdev->gpu_reset);
+    usleep_range(10, 20);
+    reset_control_deassert(kbdev->gpu_reset);
+}
+```
+
+### 8.3 RCSU Registers
+
+The RCSU (Reset and Clock Sequencing Unit) provides platform-specific control:
+
+```c
+enum gpu_rcsu_hwreg {
+    GPU_RCSU_HWREG_PGCTRL,     // Power gate control
+    GPU_RCSU_HWREG_STRAP_PIN1, // Harvesting/strap configuration
+    GPU_RCSU_HWREG_MAX
+};
+
+#define GPU_RCSU_QCHANNEL_CLOCK_GATE_ENABLE (1 << 0)
+
+// Enable Q-channel clock gating
+static int gpu_qchannel_clock_gating_switch(struct kbase_device *kbdev, bool enable) {
+    reg = sky1_rcsu_reg_read32(kbdev, GPU_RCSU_HWREG_PGCTRL);
+    reg = enable ? (reg | GPU_RCSU_QCHANNEL_CLOCK_GATE_ENABLE) :
+                   (reg & ~GPU_RCSU_QCHANNEL_CLOCK_GATE_ENABLE);
+    sky1_rcsu_reg_write32(kbdev, GPU_RCSU_HWREG_PGCTRL, reg);
+}
+```
+
+### 8.4 Sky1 Power Model
+
+Sky1 has a custom power model for thermal management:
+
+```c
+bool enable_sky1_power_model = true;
+module_param(enable_sky1_power_model, bool, 0660);
+
+// Timer-based power monitoring
+static enum hrtimer_restart sky1_power_timer_callback(struct hrtimer *timer) {
+    if (enable_sky1_power_model) {
+        queue_work(kbdev->sky1_power_wq, &kbdev->sky1_power_work);
+    }
+    // Re-arm timer every 100ms
+    hrtimer_forward_now(timer, ms_to_ktime(100));
+    return HRTIMER_RESTART;
+}
+```
+
+---
+
+## 9. Power Flow Summary
+
+### 9.1 Firmware-Controlled Mode (`firmware_hctl_core_pwr = false`)
+
+```
+1. L2 power-on -> DELEGATE(TILER, SHADER, NEURAL) to MCU
+2. MCU boots, receives GLB_ALLOC_EN with available cores
+3. MCU receives GLB_PWROFF_TIMER with timeout value
+4. During job execution:
+   - MCU powers cores via HOST_POWER interface
+   - MCU sets SHADER_PWRACTIVE when cores execute
+   - MCU powers off idle cores after timeout
+5. L2 power-off -> RETRACT(TILER, SHADER, NEURAL) from MCU
+```
+
+### 9.2 Host-Controlled Mode (`firmware_hctl_core_pwr = true`)
+
+```
+1. L2 power-on -> RETRACT (ensure host has control)
+2. Host powers shaders via SHADER_PWRON register
+3. Host waits for SHADER_READY
+4. Host notifies MCU via kbase_csf_firmware_update_core_attr()
+   - GLB_ALLOC_EN set to powered cores
+   - GLB_PWROFF_TIMER set to 0 (disabled)
+5. MCU boots, uses already-powered cores
+6. MCU does NOT use HOST_POWER for job activation
+7. During job execution:
+   - Cores already powered by host
+   - MCU just dispatches jobs
+8. L2 power-off -> Host powers down shaders
+```
+
+---
+
+## 10. Key Implications for Sky1/Panthor
+
+### 10.1 Why Host-Controlled Mode Exists
+
+The `firmware_hctl_core_pwr` mode exists because:
+1. Some platforms may not have working HOST_POWER interface
+2. `always_on` policy benefits from keeping cores powered
+3. Debugging/testing without MCU power management
+
+### 10.2 Sky1 HOST_POWER Status
+
+On Sky1, HOST_POWER registers return 0x0:
+- `PWR_STATUS` = 0x0 (no domains allowed/delegated)
+- `HOST_POWER_SHADER_PWRACTIVE` = 0x0 (no active cores via HOST_POWER)
+
+This explains why:
+1. DELEGATE command times out (no status bits change)
+2. RETRACT command times out (no status bits change)
+3. Legacy `SHADER_PWRON` works (0x180 register)
+4. MCU can't activate cores for jobs (tries HOST_POWER internally)
+
+### 10.3 Vendor Driver Workaround
+
+The vendor driver likely uses `firmware_hctl_core_pwr = true` on Sky1:
+1. Uses `always_on` policy or sets `mcu_shader_pwroff_timeout = 0`
+2. Host powers cores via legacy registers
+3. Sets `GLB_PWROFF_TIMER = 0` to disable MCU power management
+4. Notifies MCU of powered cores via `GLB_ALLOC_EN`
+5. MCU dispatches jobs to pre-powered cores
+
